    {
      "id": "b0e60dfecce62eba6e68573df1e4a96c628e18a7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-14 22:00:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI just ran iozone with 16 threads which can saturate QDR network with 3.2GB/s throughput.\n\nDoes patch 5034 help out?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "67e8741b4cb797525407559f562ed50de299826f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-14 22:15:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI don't think we've ran with 5034 so I can't say for sure, but I doubt it will help us since it's only called on unmount. The case we need to address is contention on cl_envs_guard in ll_releasepage.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "6b194c7a468b98f225d3141eedd1403d9c92082a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-14 22:17:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nHow much RAM does the system have that OOM'd during your testing? I might try to reproduce that failure.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "aaf83c8fe56be83811f8993403bb8054d2173587",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-14 22:28:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nHold, I ran it again. Patch 5204 may be good. It hit LU-2398 and crash kernel took system over. It appeared the crash kernel is configured wrong so OOM happened.\n\nI applied the patch in LU-2398 and it seems okay now.\n\nBut this patch(5446) surely causes OOM.\n\nMy node has 32G memory",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "a3811165a6e162f2927e6e5ae58ca24da1b9be7f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-14 22:51:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nOK. Thanks for the update. I can easily patch set 2 of this one causing issues when cl_env_percpu_get returns NULL. Like I said before, we can fall back to using cl_env_get but that might nullify the whole point of this patch.\n\nIf ll_releasepage is going to be largely reworked, I'd suggest dropping the need for an env in that call path altogether. If we can just pass in a NULL pointer and ensure the underlying functions can handle that, it would probably help quite a bit over the performance of 5204.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "6ae7c0eb212d65da00bf0f2084ab073d5efefbb0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-14 23:01:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nYes, it will be ideal if we can get rid of env for ll_releasepage(). Let's see.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
